<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: CARSON; SHERIFF'S DEPT. WILL ENFORCE YOUTH CURFEW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY GUTHRIE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a bid to curb graffiti and other crimes by young people, the Los Angeles 
County Sheriff's Department will begin to strictly enforce a 10 p.m. curfew 
starting Friday for youths under the age of 18. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the department's new policy, youths who cannot prove they are en route 
to a specific destination, or who do not have written permission from a parent 
to be out, will be in violation of the curfew. 
</P>
<P>
 In the past, youngsters would have been cited and released. But now young 
people detained by deputies will be held at the station until arrangements can 
be made with their parents to pick them up. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides calling parents, deputies also will issue citations for violating the 
curfew. 
</P>
<P>
 "Our hope is to cut down on the graffiti and vandalism that occurs," said Sgt. 
Steve Bellino of the Carson station. 
</P>
<P>
 The fine for curfew violations can be up to $1,000 and/or six months in jail, 
police officials said.  
</P>
<P>
 MARY GUTHRIE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
