<HEADLINE>
<P>
END OF THE LINE FOR MIAMI TROLLEYS AS FEAR TAKES TOLL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The operators of a trolley service say they are halting their sightseeing 
tours of Miami because fear and violence are scaring riders away. 
</P>
<P>
 Old Town Trolleys, headquartered in Key West, Fla., will end its tours of 
Miami on July 31, according to a story in Wednesday's Miami Herald. The company 
has ferried 500,000 passengers to attractions throughout Miami in the past six 
years. 
</P>
<P>
 Chief Executive Officer Christopher Belland said ridership dwindled to fewer 
than 40,000 last year. He blamed media reports that have heightened the fear of 
random violence, and hotel concierges, taxi drivers and local residents who 
advise visitors not to leave the safety of their seaside hotels. 
</P>
