<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF NOTEBOOK / MARTIN BECK; WOODS TAKES ANOTHER STEP FORWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN BECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tiger Woods, the only male to win three U.S. Junior Amateur golf titles, made 
another breakthrough Saturday in spectacular fashion. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods, 18, of Cypress, won the Pacific Northwest Amateur in Vancouver, Wash., 
routed Ted Snavely, 11 and 10, in the championship match on the 6,818-yard 
course at Royal Oaks Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the first victory in a non-junior event for Woods, who will attend 
Stanford in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods closed out Snavely, the Oregon State Amateur champion who plays for the 
University of Oregon, on the 26th hole of a scheduled 36-hole match. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods shot nine-under-par 63 -- nine birdies and nine pars -- in the morning 
and was 13-under for the day when he won. He needed only 30 putts to complete 
the 26 holes. 
</P>
<P>
 "That was the best round of my life," Woods said Monday, "because I didn't hit 
the ball all that great but I hit all the right spots and made my putts." 
</P>
<P>
 The course record of 64 still stands because Woods was conceded three putts, 
the longest of which was about 18 inches. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods was the medalist in the two-round stroke-play qualifying for match play, 
shooting 68-69. In his 140 holes in the tournament, Woods was 35-under par. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods was at the top of his game despite suffering with a head cold. "Beware 
of the sick man," he said. "Isn't it always like that in sports: every time 
you're sick you play well. It was one of those weeks that everything came 
together." 
</P>
<P>
 Woods hopes his performance this summer will earn him a spot on the U.S. team 
for the World Amateur team championship in October in France. Woods will play 
in three more amateur tournaments -- the Southern California Golf Assn. 
Amateur, the Porter Cup in New York, and the Western Amateur in Michigan, 
before attempting to qualify for the U.S. Amateur in August. 
</P>
<P>
 Woods said he is especially looking forward to this weekend's SCGA Amateur 
Friday through Sunday at Hacienda Golf Club in La Habra Heights. 
</P>
<P>
 "All my friends will be there to watch," Woods said. "My best friend (fellow 
Western High graduate Bryon Bell) is going to caddie for me. So it's kind of 
nice." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The SCGA starts at 7 a.m. Friday for two rounds after which a cut will be made 
to the low 42 and ties. Play starts at 7:30 a.m. Saturday and Sunday. Hacienda 
Golf Club, 718 East Rd. in La Habra Heights, can be reached from Harbor 
Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Kemp Richardson of Laguna Niguel is also entered in the SCGA Amateur, but he 
doesn't fit the profile of most entrants. Richardson is 48; most of his 
competitors are of college age. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you go to an amateur tournament that's pretty much what you'll find," 
Richardson said. "You'll find a few guys my age but you'll have to look pretty 
hard." 
</P>
<P>
 But tough competition keeps him coming back, said Richardson, who was a 
two-time Pacific 8 Conference champion in 1967 and '68 and a first-team 
All-American at USC. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wouldn't enjoy just going out and playing," he said. "I'd rather still try 
to be somewhat competitive. Not that I don't like playing but I wouldn't want 
just a steady diet of it." 
</P>
<P>
 Richardson finished second in the SCGA Amateur in 1966 and '68, losing the '66 
title to John Jacobs on the third playoff hole. 
</P>
<P>
 Richardson's father, John, won the SCGA Amateur title in 1973 and the 1987 
U.S. Senior Amateur. John Richardson died in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
 Kemp Richardson, a stockbroker, carries a plus-1.9 index at El Niguel Country 
Club, but isn't able to practice as much as he would like because of a bad 
back. 
</P>
<P>
 The back forced him out of qualifying for June's California Amateur, but he 
still went up to Pebble Beach to caddie for his son, Scott. 
</P>
<P>
 Carrying a bag with a bad back? 
</P>
<P>
 "I made it through 15 holes the first day and he had to take over," Richardson 
said. "I made it nine holes the next day." 
</P>
<P>
 Scott, a former Dana Hills High standout who played for Saddleback College in 
1993 and will transfer to USC in the fall, didn't make the cut to match play. 
</P>
<P>
 Scott won't be playing in the SCGA tournament because he lost a six-way 
playoff for five spots in qualifying. Kemp was among the five who qualified. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Coto de Caza's Kellee Booth is playing in the U.S. Women's Open this week at 
Indianwood Golf and Country Club in Lake Orion, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
 Booth, who graduated from Santa Margarita High in June and will attend Arizona 
State, won the U.S. Girls' Junior title last year. This is her first U.S. Open. 
</P>
