<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS / COSTA MESA / NEWPORT / IRVINE: IRVINE; FAMILY SEEKING 
DELAY ON RAZING OF HOME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Superior Court judge on Wednesday agreed to rule next month on a request by 
the Ganish family to delay the planned demolition of their castle-like home 
until a court decides whether Irvine's public-nuisance laws are constitutional. 
</P>
<P>
 The move comes a week after the City Council declared the Kron Street home a 
public nuisance. The council said that exposed wires and debris inside the 
unfinished structure make it a fire hazard. 
</P>
<P>
 The council gave Fern and Haym Ganish until October to meet city codes or the 
city would tear it down. 
</P>
<P>
 But the Ganishes' attorney, Robert Sainburg, contends that the city's nuisance 
law is "unconstitutionally vague and over-broad." 
</P>
<P>
 Sainburg said he will ask Superior Court Judge Nancy Wieben Stock at an Aug. 
18 hearing to temporarily halt the demolition proceedings until the court rules 
on the constitutionality of the laws. 
</P>
<P>
 If the city's nuisance rules are struck down, the city might eventually be 
forced to write new laws, Sainburg said. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy City Attorney Patrick Munoz said Wednesday he is "confident that the 
judge will rule in our favor." 
</P>
<P>
 The Ganishes began transforming their ranch-style home into a two-story 
mansion with rock facade more than 12 years ago. The remodeling work is still 
not completed. The Ganishes continue to live in the home even though the 
interior lacks drywall, ceiling materials, plumbing and proper electrical 
wiring. 
</P>
<P>
 City code inspectors and county fire officials said the exposed wires could 
spark a blaze. 
</P>
<P>
 The city has pressed the Ganishes for years to complete construction. Fern 
Ganish said work has been stalled in part because of her husband's poor health. 
</P>
<P>
 Sainburg said the Ganishes are willing to discuss the issues with city 
officials. He objected to the city's demand that any visits to the home by 
building inspectors be videotaped. 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't want to make a circus out of this with videotape," Sainburg said. 
</P>
<P>
 Munoz said the city wants the video recording so that "we have an absolutely 
accurate record of what occurred." SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</TEXT>
