<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITYWIDE SEARCH CONTINUES FOR 6-YEAR-OLD GIRL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NICHOLAS RICCARDI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It has been three weeks, but Jane Newman believes her daughter is still trying 
to come home. 
</P>
<P>
 "I feel in my heart that she's probably looking for me and is going in the 
wrong direction," Newman said. 
</P>
<P>
 Newman's daughter, Crystal Tymich, has been missing since June 30. Police and 
the FBI are scouring the city to find the 6-year-old. There has been one 
large-scale sweep of the South-Central Los Angeles neighborhood where Crystal 
disappeared, and police may search that area again or bring in a psychic to try 
to find Crystal. 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council is posting a $10,000 reward for her return. 
</P>
<P>
 Crystal grew up in South-Central but now splits time between her mother's home 
in Santa Monica and her father's in the Hyde Park district near Inglewood. The 
day she disappeared, she was near her father's home, playing with her three 
brothers, ages 12, 10 and 8, in the 6000 block of Bryhurst Avenue. The brothers 
were riding on bicycles ahead of her, and when they turned around to look back 
about 2 p.m., Crystal was gone. 
</P>
<P>
 Newman said neighbors had seen Crystal wandering off other times that day and 
had brought her back to her brothers. She said Crystal had been talking about 
running away. 
</P>
<P>
 Police say they have no solid leads. However, after a television report on 
Crystal's disappearance, police received calls from people who said they 
thought they had seen her in Downey, Santa Fe Springs and Bell Gardens. The 
girl was last seen wearing a pink T-shirt, flowered shorts and white tennis 
shoes with a Little Mermaid design. She is about 4 feet tall with brown hair 
and brown eyes. 
</P>
<P>
 "One minute she was playing with her brothers four or five houses away, and 
the next minute she vanished in broad daylight," said Officer Tim McRath, who 
is investigating the case. "We haven't ruled anything out." 
</P>
<P>
 Police are considering using a psychic to help find Crystal, a technique 
sometimes employed in missing person cases. "We're trying for anything now," 
said Officer Robert Castaneda, McRath's partner. 
</P>
<P>
 Newman said Crystal enjoys arcades and might be seen around video games or 
stores. Anyone who sees Crystal is asked to call police at (213) 485-4164, 
(213) 485-4175 or 911. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm just praying every day for my daughter," Newman said. "She's a very 
high-spirited girl. She's a fighter." 
</P>
</TEXT>
